        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "## Diagnosis\n\nThe \"Start Run\" flow was failing because **`ConfirmDialog` did not await the async `onConfirm` handler**.\n\n### What was happening\n\n1. User clicks **Start Run** → confirm dialog opens.\n2. User clicks **Confirm & Start** → `handleConfirm` runs.\n3. `handleConfirm` called `onConfirm()` (which starts `executeRun()`) and then immediately called `handleClose()`.\n4. `executeRun()` is async and returns a Promise, but the dialog did not await it.\n5. The dialog closed right away, before the API call finished.\n6. If the API failed, `formError` was set, but the dialog had already closed and the form could be in a confusing state.\n7. If the API succeeded, the form hid and the list refreshed, but the timing could feel inconsistent.\n\n### Root cause\n\nIn `ConfirmDialog`:\n\n```tsx\nconst handleConfirm = () => {\n  onConfirm();   // fires executeRun() — returns immediately (async)\n  handleClose(); // runs immediately — dialog closes before API completes\n};\n```\n\n`onConfirm` was invoked but its Promise was never awaited, so the dialog closed before the async work finished.\n\n---\n\n## Fixes applied\n\n1. **`ConfirmDialog` now awaits async `onConfirm`**\n   - If `onConfirm` returns a Promise, the dialog waits for it to resolve.\n   - A loading state shows (\"Starting…\") while the request runs.\n   - The dialog closes only after the async work completes (success or error).\n   - On error, the dialog closes so the user can see the form error message.\n\n2. **Disabled-state feedback for Start Run**\n   - When the button is disabled (no model or prompt version), a `title` tooltip explains why:\n     - \"Select a model first\"\n     - \"Enter prompt version\"\n\nAll tests pass. You can verify by clicking **Start Run** → **Confirm & Start**; the dialog should stay open until the API call finishes and show \"Starting…\" during the request.",
